T2  - JOURNAL OF EXPERIMENTAL MARINE BIOLOGY AND ECOLOGY
M3  - Article
AB  - Utilization of C-14-labeled lignocellulose by the ribbed mussel Geukensia demissa (Dillwyn) was evaluated under simulated intertidal (50/50% exposure/submergence) and subtidal (100% submergence) conditions.  Ingestation rates of mussels fed on [C-14] lignocellulose did not differ significantly between mussels held in intertidal and subtidal conditions.  The mean ( +/- SE) C-14 absorption efficiency for intertidal mussels fed [C-14] lignocellulose was 14.9 +/- 0.5% in summer (June 1986) and 6.7 +/- 0.5% in fall (October 1988).  Mean ( +/- SE) summer (9.1 +/- 0.6%) and fall (4.0 +/- 0.2%) C-14 absorption efficiencies of subtidal mussels fed [C-14] lignocellulose were significantly lower (t test, p < 0.05) than those of intertidal mussels.  It was estimated that the contribution of lignocellulose to the total summer energy requirements of intertidal and subtidal G. demissa was similar at 5.7 and 5.3%, respectively.  Reduced metabolic expenditures and higher absorption efficiencies allow G. demissa to compensate for a limited period of feeding on lignocellulose in its intertidal habitat.
