AB  - Macroalgae contribute to intertidal food webs primarily as detritus, with unclear implications for food web studies using stable isotope analysis. We examined differences in the thallus parts of two South African rhodophytes (Gelidium pristoides and Hypnea spicifera) and changes in overall delta(13)C, delta(15)N signatures and C:N ratios during degradation in both the field and laboratory. We hypothesized that both degrading macroalgal tissue and macroalgal-derived suspended particulate material (SPM) would show negligible changes in delta(13)C, but enriched delta(15)N signatures and lower C:N ratios relative to healthy plants. Only C:N laboratory ratios conformed to predictions, with both species of macroalgae showing decomposition related changes in delta(13)C and significant depletions in delta(15)N in both the field and laboratory. In the laboratory, algal tissue and SPM from each species behaved similarly (though some effects were non-significant) but with differing strengths. Gelidium pristoides delta(13)C increased and C:N ratios decreased over time in tissue and SPM; delta(15)N became depleted only in SPM. Hypnea spicifera, delta(13)C, delta(15)N and C:N ratios all decreased during degradation in both SPM and algae.Over 60 days in the field, delta(13)C was depleted in both species (1-2 parts per thousand) and in naturally senescent Gelidium pristoides fronds. delta(15)N was depleted in Hypnea spicifera (approx. 1 parts per thousand), while C:N ratios of both species were unaffected. The two species differed in delta(13)C, delta(15)N and C:N after degradation, but only in C:N beforehand. We suggest isotope changes in the laboratory mainly reflect microbial effects, while in the field these are combined with leaching due to constant water replenishment and agitation. Differences between these two species in the isotope responses to degradation highlight the difficulty of linking the signature of SPM to its multiple sources. (C) 2009 Elsevier Ltd. All rig