AB  - The marsh littoral zone of Lake Okeechobee is approximately 40,000 acres of wetland fringing the third largest lake in the United States. Vegetation changes occurring in the marsh between 1989 and 1992 were related to various soil and hydrologic parameters. In order to develop the environmental parameter databases, a hydrologic model was used to spatially portray the movement of water over the marsh and a grid sampling survey of soil nutrients was done to map soil parameters. Changes in vegetation communities were related to short hydroperiods, low soil organic matter and high soil bulk density. Melaleuca continues to invade the marsh, aided by short hydroperiods in some areas. Areas with high soil phosphorus seem to be associated with many of the disturbed areas.
